Let $\cos^2 x = c, \sin^2 x = s$ $\implies s + c = 1$. Expanding the determinant, we get:

c\begin{vmatrix} \cos^2 x & 1 \\ \cot^2 x & \csc^2 x \end{vmatrix}
- 1\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & \csc^2 x \end{vmatrix}
+ 1\begin{vmatrix} 1 & \cos^2 x \\ 1 & \cos^2 x \end{vmatrix} \\
&= c(c \csc^2 x - \cot^2 x s) - (\cot^2 x - \csc^2 x) \\
&= c(c^2 - \frac{1}{c^2}(1 - c) - \frac{1 - c}{c^2}), \text{ substituting } s = 1 - c \\
&= c^2 - 2 + c \text{, I think. } \\
\end{vmatrix}
\end{think}

