Notice that $D^2 = D$ because $D$ is idempotent (i.e., $D \cdot D = D$). 

Also, $C$ is a scalar multiple of the identity matrix, and the determinant of a matrix of the form $C + D$ is the sum of the determinants of $C + Dv$ for any eigenvector $v$ of $D$ with eigenvalue 1.

We observe that $D$ has a single eigenvalue of 1, which is found by solving $Dv = v$. For instance, \begin{align*}
    D 
    & = \begin{bmatrix}
       0 & 1 & 1 \\
       \cos^2 x & 0 & \sin^2 x \\
       0 & 0 & \cos^2 x \\
    \end{bmatrix}
  \end{align*} 
  has a normal vector $v = \begin{bmatrix} -\sin^2 x \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}$ because $D$ must map it to itself, as $Dv = 1 \cdot v$.

Writing $C + D = C + Dv$ indicates that the determinant is simply the sum of the eigenvalues of $C + D$, which are the eigenvalues of $C$ plus one.

Thus, the eigenvalues of $C + D$ are $c + 1$ (with multiplicity 3), and the determinant is $(c + 1)^3 = (1 - \cos^2 x + 1)^3 = 2^3 = 8$. <answer>

